hook.real_world_problem:
You're building a recommendation engine. Every time a user views a product, you record it — and you must not recommend products they've ALREADY seen. With ArrayList:

```java
List<String> seenProducts = new ArrayList<>();

// Record a view
if (!seenProducts.contains(productId)) {
    seenProducts.add(productId);
}

// Check before recommending:
if (!seenProducts.contains(candidateProduct)) {
    recommend(candidateProduct);
}
```

Both calls to `contains()` scan the ENTIRE list. After 10,000 views, each check scans up to 10,000 items. A million-user app with millions of viewed products? It crawls.

With HashSet:

```java
Set<String> seenProducts = new HashSet<>();

seenProducts.add(productId);      // O(1)

if (!seenProducts.contains(candidateProduct)) {  // O(1)
    recommend(candidateProduct);
}
```

**Constant time.** 10,000 items or 10 million — same speed. HashSet is backed by a HashMap, so it inherits O(1) lookup.

Plus: HashSet AUTOMATICALLY prevents duplicates. If you add the same item twice, it's only stored once. No `if (!contains) add` needed — just `add()` and it handles uniqueness.

This is HashSet: O(1) membership checking + automatic deduplication. After List and Map, it's the third essential collection.

concept_explanation.intro:
A **HashSet** is an unordered collection of UNIQUE elements — no duplicates, no guaranteed order. It's backed by a HashMap (without values), giving O(1) average operations.

```java
import java.util.HashSet;
import java.util.Set;

Set<String> tags = new HashSet<>();

tags.add("java");      // OK
tags.add("oop");       // OK
tags.add("java");      // IGNORED — already present

System.out.println(tags.size());           // 2 (not 3)
System.out.println(tags.contains("oop"));  // true — O(1)
System.out.println(tags.contains("python")); // false — O(1)

tags.remove("oop");   // remove if present

for (String tag : tags) {   // iterate (no guaranteed order)
    System.out.println(tag);
}
```

Key properties:
- `add()` silently ignores duplicates (returns false if already present, true if added)
- `contains()` is O(1) — this is the MAIN REASON to use HashSet
- Order is NOT guaranteed — different from List

concept_explanation.deduplication_pattern:
**The deduplication pattern** — instantly remove duplicates from a list:

```java
List<String> withDuplicates = Arrays.asList(
    "apple", "banana", "apple", "cherry", "banana"
);

// Deduplicate: wrap in HashSet, then optionally back to List
Set<String> unique = new HashSet<>(withDuplicates);
System.out.println(unique);  // [banana, apple, cherry] (any order)

// If you need a List again (with no duplicates):
List<String> deduped = new ArrayList<>(unique);
```

`new HashSet<>(collection)` is the most idiomatic Java deduplication. Works instantly.

**What makes it work**: HashSet's constructor accepts any Collection. It calls add() for each element — duplicates silently ignored.

**Note**: order is NOT preserved. If you need deduplication WITH insertion order, use `LinkedHashSet` instead — preserves the order elements were first added.

concept_explanation.set_operations:
Three classic set operations — all achievable with HashSet:

**Union** (all elements from both sets):
```java
Set<String> a = new HashSet<>(Arrays.asList("A", "B", "C"));
Set<String> b = new HashSet<>(Arrays.asList("B", "C", "D"));

Set<String> union = new HashSet<>(a);
union.addAll(b);  // adds all of b; duplicates ignored
// Result: {A, B, C, D}
```

**Intersection** (only elements in BOTH sets):
```java
Set<String> intersection = new HashSet<>(a);
intersection.retainAll(b);  // keep only elements also in b
// Result: {B, C}
```

**Difference** (elements in a but NOT in b):
```java
Set<String> difference = new HashSet<>(a);
difference.removeAll(b);  // remove everything that's in b
// Result: {A}
```

**Key**: always operate on a COPY to avoid mutating the original.

**Real-world uses**:
- Recommendation: userInterests MINUS alreadySeen = new recommendations
- Access control: requiredPermissions MINUS userPermissions = missing permissions
- Product comparison: featuresOfA.intersection(featuresOfB) = common features

concept_explanation.visited_pattern:
**The 'seen/visited' pattern** — track what's been processed:

```java
Set<String> visitedUrls = new HashSet<>();

List<String> urlQueue = new ArrayList<>();
urlQueue.add("https://codequest.io/");

while (!urlQueue.isEmpty()) {
    String url = urlQueue.remove(0);

    if (visitedUrls.contains(url)) {
        continue;  // skip — already processed
    }

    visitedUrls.add(url);  // mark as seen
    // process url...
    // find links in page and add to urlQueue
}
```

This is the literal architecture of every web crawler. The `visitedUrls` set prevents infinite loops (A links to B, B links back to A).

**Other uses**:
- Deduplicating event processing (same event ID arrives twice → skip)
- Tracking sent emails (don't send twice)
- Memoization (have we computed this result before?)
- Cycle detection in graphs

concept_explanation.hashset_requires_hashcode:
Like HashMap keys, objects stored in HashSet MUST have proper `hashCode()` and `equals()` — they're used to find the right bucket and confirm equality.

```java
class Tag {
    String value;
    Tag(String value) { this.value = value; }
    // No hashCode/equals override
}

Set<Tag> tags = new HashSet<>();
tags.add(new Tag("java"));
tags.add(new Tag("java"));  // different object, same value

System.out.println(tags.size());  // 2! — both stored
// Wrong — wanted 1 unique tag
```

Fix — override hashCode and equals:
```java
@Override public boolean equals(Object o) {
    if (!(o instanceof Tag t)) return false;
    return Objects.equals(this.value, t.value);
}
@Override public int hashCode() { return Objects.hash(value); }
// Now set.size() == 1 for two Tags with same value
```

For Strings, Integers, and other built-in types: they already have proper equals/hashCode. For your own classes: you must override both (Topic 4.4).

step_by_step_solution.details:
```java
class Article {
    private final String title;
    private final Set<String> tags = new HashSet<>();

    public Article(String title, String... initialTags) {
        this.title = title;
        for (String tag : initialTags) tags.add(tag);
    }

    public void addTag(String tag) { tags.add(tag); }
    public boolean hasTag(String tag) { return tags.contains(tag); }  // O(1)
    public Set<String> getTags() { return new HashSet<>(tags); }       // defensive copy
    public String getTitle() { return title; }

    @Override public String toString() { return title + " " + tags; }
}
```

`tags` is a Set — automatic deduplication. `hasTag()` is O(1). `getTags()` returns a defensive copy (caller can't modify internal set).

```java
class TagCatalog {
    private List<Article> articles = new ArrayList<>();

    public void add(Article a) { articles.add(a); }

    // Find articles that have ALL specified tags (intersection check)
    public List<Article> findWithAllTags(Set<String> required) {
        List<Article> result = new ArrayList<>();
        for (Article a : articles) {
            if (a.getTags().containsAll(required)) {
                result.add(a);
            }
        }
        return result;
    }

    // All unique tags across ALL articles (union)
    public Set<String> allTags() {
        Set<String> all = new HashSet<>();
        for (Article a : articles) {
            all.addAll(a.getTags());  // union: HashSet ignores duplicates
        }
        return all;
    }

    // Tags appearing in at least minArticles articles
    public Set<String> popularTags(int minArticles) {
        // Count occurrences per tag (HashMap for counting)
        Map<String, Integer> tagCount = new HashMap<>();
        for (Article a : articles) {
            for (String tag : a.getTags()) {
                tagCount.put(tag, tagCount.getOrDefault(tag, 0) + 1);
            }
        }

        // Filter to popular ones
        Set<String> popular = new HashSet<>();
        for (Map.Entry<String, Integer> e : tagCount.entrySet()) {
            if (e.getValue() >= minArticles) popular.add(e.getKey());
        }
        return popular;
    }
}
```

